WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.075 --> 00:00:03.450
ANDREW: We've got
a special guest

00:00:03.450 --> 00:00:06.350
with us today,
Jennifer Pharr Davis.

00:00:06.350 --> 00:00:11.370
She's logged over 12,000 miles
on six different continents,

00:00:11.370 --> 00:00:14.520
including trails like
Pacific Crest Trail, Colorado

00:00:14.520 --> 00:00:17.930
Trail, the Appalachian Trail.

00:00:17.930 --> 00:00:20.060
She has a new book,
"Called Again,"

00:00:20.060 --> 00:00:25.730
which chronicles her journey of
47 miles per day over 46 days.

00:00:25.730 --> 00:00:27.850
And she's been featured
on the "New York Times,"

00:00:27.850 --> 00:00:30.310
"Washington Post,"
"Talk of the Nation,"

00:00:30.310 --> 00:00:32.299
"Daily Beast"--
the list goes on.

00:00:33.350 --> 00:00:36.475
She's agreed to come here
and give a talk to us today,

00:00:36.475 --> 00:00:37.850
and I'm very
excited to have her.

00:00:37.850 --> 00:00:40.915
So please help me welcome
Jennifer Pharr Davis.

00:00:40.915 --> 00:00:43.705
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:46.334 --> 00:00:48.000
JENNIFER DAVIS: It's
always fun to share

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:49.530
some of my hiking stories.

00:00:49.530 --> 00:00:51.490
And like Andrew said,
I've been able to hike

00:00:51.490 --> 00:00:54.490
all over the world on
six different continents.

00:00:54.490 --> 00:00:56.770
I have not been to
Antarctica, because I'm

00:00:56.770 --> 00:00:59.970
a wimp in cold weather,
which we talked about.

00:00:59.970 --> 00:01:03.980
But of all the places where I
have hiked and I have traveled,

00:01:03.980 --> 00:01:06.060
the one trail that
means the most to me,

00:01:06.060 --> 00:01:08.660
and the trail that has
changed my life the most,

00:01:08.660 --> 00:01:11.364
is the Appalachian Trail.

00:01:11.364 --> 00:01:13.030
And where I come from
in North Carolina,

00:01:13.030 --> 00:01:15.990
we call it the
"Appa-lah-chin" Trail.

00:01:15.990 --> 00:01:18.970
You may have heard of the
"Appa-lay-shin" Trail, right?

00:01:18.970 --> 00:01:21.400
Well, that's not correct,
just so you know.

00:01:21.400 --> 00:01:22.730
It's the "Appa-lah-chin" Trail.

00:01:22.730 --> 00:01:24.360
Or at least we can
all agree on the AT.

00:01:26.560 --> 00:01:33.340
And I've done the entire 2,185
mile AT three separate times.

00:01:34.550 --> 00:01:36.740
And it was the most
recent time in 2011

00:01:36.740 --> 00:01:39.250
where, with my husband's
help, and a whole lot of help

00:01:39.250 --> 00:01:42.520
from friends, and family,
and hikers, and runners,

00:01:42.520 --> 00:01:44.790
we set the overall record.

00:01:44.790 --> 00:01:49.700
So for 46 straight days I
averaged 47 miles a day.

00:01:51.960 --> 00:01:53.970
And that's crazy,
exactly, right?

00:01:53.970 --> 00:01:54.640
Someone said it.

00:01:54.640 --> 00:02:00.160
Yes, we can all agree
that that's crazy.

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:03.570
But hopefully, we can
also agree that a journey

00:02:03.570 --> 00:02:05.990
of any distance or
any speed is always

00:02:05.990 --> 00:02:08.340
going to start
with a single step.

00:02:08.340 --> 00:02:08.840
Yes?

00:02:10.789 --> 00:02:12.930
And my first step
into the wilderness

00:02:12.930 --> 00:02:15.610
didn't take place until
I was 21 years old.

00:02:16.825 --> 00:02:18.160
And that is so sad.

00:02:19.430 --> 00:02:19.990
It is.

00:02:19.990 --> 00:02:21.890
I grew up in a beautiful area.

00:02:21.890 --> 00:02:24.710
But nowadays, with
school being so

00:02:24.710 --> 00:02:28.000
demanding, and extracurriculars
taking up so much time,

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:31.760
unless your family's really
focused on going outdoors,

00:02:31.760 --> 00:02:34.910
you're not going to spend a
whole lot of time in nature.

00:02:34.910 --> 00:02:38.705
So I graduated from college,
and I didn't know anything

00:02:38.705 --> 00:02:39.580
about the wilderness.

00:02:40.790 --> 00:02:42.940
And that really bothered me.

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:44.700
And I felt like because
I didn't know much

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:47.795
about the natural world, I
really didn't know myself.

00:02:49.370 --> 00:02:52.620
So I wanted to take some
time to try and fix that.

00:02:53.850 --> 00:02:55.430
And growing up in
North Carolina,

00:02:55.430 --> 00:02:57.540
I'd heard about the
Appalachian Trail.

00:02:58.570 --> 00:03:01.170
I had never set
foot on it before.

00:03:01.170 --> 00:03:03.010
In fact, I'd only
spent two nights

00:03:03.010 --> 00:03:04.870
in the woods my entire life.

00:03:06.060 --> 00:03:11.170
But the good news is, at age
21, that doesn't matter, right?

00:03:11.170 --> 00:03:14.120
Inexperience never seems
to matter to 21 year old.

00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:16.660
And I decided that I was
going to get out and do

00:03:16.660 --> 00:03:18.670
that entire trail by myself.

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:23.490
So I started on my own, with my
brother's old Boy Scout gear,

00:03:23.490 --> 00:03:24.240
in Georgia.

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:29.210
And my goal was to walk
all the way up to Maine.

00:03:31.730 --> 00:03:33.890
And that first journey,
I was out there

00:03:33.890 --> 00:03:38.380
for five full months, which
is very standard when you're

00:03:38.380 --> 00:03:40.912
trying to hike the entire trail.

00:03:40.912 --> 00:03:44.870
But at the time, it was
the five hardest months

00:03:44.870 --> 00:03:45.750
I had ever known.

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:51.270
And even though it was 10 years
ago, I'll still today say,

00:03:51.270 --> 00:03:55.475
it was also the five best
months of my entire life.

00:03:56.670 --> 00:03:59.330
Because the trail
completely changed me.

00:03:59.330 --> 00:04:00.200
And I needed that.

00:04:00.200 --> 00:04:02.190
I liked the woman at
the end a heck of a lot

00:04:02.190 --> 00:04:04.290
more than the girl who started.

00:04:05.430 --> 00:04:07.700
And I could spend
all day telling you

00:04:07.700 --> 00:04:09.470
about that first journey.

00:04:09.470 --> 00:04:10.690
It was so foundational.

00:04:10.690 --> 00:04:12.670
I could tell you
lessons I learned,

00:04:12.670 --> 00:04:15.590
describe folks I met along
the way-- because, trust me,

00:04:15.590 --> 00:04:16.590
there's some characters.

00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:20.380
But you guys are at work.

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:21.700
You don't have all day.

00:04:21.700 --> 00:04:24.150
We got to get you back and
being productive and solving

00:04:24.150 --> 00:04:25.310
all the Google problems.

00:04:25.310 --> 00:04:27.960
And so I'm going
to try to sum up

00:04:27.960 --> 00:04:30.050
that journey and
that transformation

00:04:30.050 --> 00:04:33.880
by reading a short passage
from my first book.

00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:38.030
And this book chronicles
my initial journey

00:04:38.030 --> 00:04:39.380
down the Appalachian Trail.

00:04:39.380 --> 00:04:41.180
And it's got a
really strange name.

00:04:41.180 --> 00:04:43.305
It's called "Becoming Odyssa."

00:04:43.305 --> 00:04:45.180
Half the people read
the book, and they still

00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:46.360
can't pronounce the title.

00:04:47.410 --> 00:04:50.810
But just so you know,
Odyssa is my trail name.

00:04:51.654 --> 00:04:53.070
And it's really
common when you go

00:04:53.070 --> 00:04:56.350
and you hike these long paths
that, while you're out there,

00:04:56.350 --> 00:04:59.890
you take a nickname that
hikers call a trail name.

00:04:59.890 --> 00:05:01.220
I know we have hikers in here.

00:05:01.220 --> 00:05:03.490
Do we have any trail names?

00:05:03.490 --> 00:05:04.737
Are you willing to share?

00:05:04.737 --> 00:05:05.320
AUDIENCE: Doc.

00:05:05.320 --> 00:05:06.440
JENNIFER DAVIS: Doc.

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:08.999
Did you take that, or was
someone else-- gave it to you?

00:05:08.999 --> 00:05:10.540
AUDIENCE: It was
kind of given to me.

00:05:10.540 --> 00:05:11.880
JENNIFER DAVIS: Kind
of given to you.

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:13.421
Well, that's the
point I'm going for.

00:05:13.421 --> 00:05:16.120
Because hikers love to
try and give other hikers

00:05:16.120 --> 00:05:16.970
their trail name.

00:05:17.990 --> 00:05:22.210
In my first week out there--
by the way, if you can't tell,

00:05:22.210 --> 00:05:24.236
I am 6 feet tall.

00:05:24.236 --> 00:05:26.110
And I've been this height
since eighth grade.

00:05:27.970 --> 00:05:30.870
And my first week on the
trail, I got suggestions

00:05:30.870 --> 00:05:35.921
like Sasquatch, Amazon,
and Stretch, yeah.

00:05:35.921 --> 00:05:38.420
And all of a sudden, all those
old wounds from middle school

00:05:38.420 --> 00:05:39.336
were just ripped open.

00:05:41.140 --> 00:05:42.900
And I don't want any of those.

00:05:42.900 --> 00:05:45.450
But then I was being a dork
and comparing the trail

00:05:45.450 --> 00:05:47.080
to Homer's "Odyssey."

00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:49.315
And another hiker said,
well, what about Odysseus?

00:05:50.590 --> 00:05:52.210
And I liked that.

00:05:52.210 --> 00:05:54.149
But I was proud to
be a woman out there.

00:05:54.149 --> 00:05:55.940
Because there weren't
that many, especially

00:05:55.940 --> 00:05:56.815
hiking by themselves.

00:05:58.240 --> 00:06:00.100
So I wanted a
feminine trail name.

00:06:00.100 --> 00:06:02.810
And we changed
Odysseus to Odyssa.

00:06:02.810 --> 00:06:04.250
And I've been Odyssa ever since.

00:06:05.540 --> 00:06:08.110
So here's a passage
from the last full day

00:06:08.110 --> 00:06:10.670
of Odyssa's first journey.

00:06:13.560 --> 00:06:18.200
"When people had asked why I
wanted to hike the Appalachian

00:06:18.200 --> 00:06:21.780
Trail, one of the
answers I had given

00:06:21.780 --> 00:06:24.670
was that I wanted time to think
about where I wanted to live

00:06:24.670 --> 00:06:26.730
and what I wanted
to do for a living.

00:06:27.890 --> 00:06:30.160
And the trail would give me
plenty of time to do that.

00:06:31.490 --> 00:06:35.130
But now that I was at the
end, I didn't feel any closer

00:06:35.130 --> 00:06:37.730
to knowing those answers
than when I started.

00:06:39.220 --> 00:06:41.050
The only thing I
felt more certain

00:06:41.050 --> 00:06:43.780
of at the end of this
journey was myself.

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:48.070
I was no longer
defined by my resume,

00:06:48.070 --> 00:06:49.850
and I didn't give
answers based on what

00:06:49.850 --> 00:06:53.190
I thought other
people wanted to hear.

00:06:53.190 --> 00:06:57.140
For the first time in my
life, I knew who I was,

00:06:57.140 --> 00:06:59.490
and I was OK with who I was.

00:07:01.410 --> 00:07:03.870
At the end of this journey,
I knew that something deep

00:07:03.870 --> 00:07:07.460
within me connected with
nature, and with hard work,

00:07:07.460 --> 00:07:08.535
and with simplicity.

00:07:09.766 --> 00:07:13.330
I also learned that I was
both stubborn and tough--

00:07:13.330 --> 00:07:16.970
a lot tougher than I
thought I was, especially

00:07:16.970 --> 00:07:23.070
when I let other people
help me along the way."

00:07:23.070 --> 00:07:29.110
Now, when it was all said
and done, I got off trail,

00:07:29.110 --> 00:07:30.650
and I got a job.

00:07:30.650 --> 00:07:35.030
I mean, much to my mother's
relief, I got a job.

00:07:35.030 --> 00:07:37.430
And it was a good job.

00:07:37.430 --> 00:07:40.890
I was working with fun people,
living in a great place.

00:07:40.890 --> 00:07:43.955
And I think everything said,
I should have been happy.

00:07:43.955 --> 00:07:45.080
I should have been content.

00:07:46.570 --> 00:07:48.220
But then the weeks
started to pass.

00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:49.700
And the months started to pass.

00:07:49.700 --> 00:07:52.940
And all I could think
about was the trail.

00:07:54.350 --> 00:07:56.160
And I missed it.

00:07:56.160 --> 00:07:57.980
I missed moving through nature.

00:07:57.980 --> 00:08:01.470
My job was great, but
it was a desk job.

00:08:01.470 --> 00:08:03.360
And I sat there for
eight hours a day.

00:08:04.530 --> 00:08:07.600
And while I sat there,
I longed for the friends

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:09.050
I had made on the trail.

00:08:10.440 --> 00:08:11.930
It was the first
environment I had

00:08:11.930 --> 00:08:14.480
been a part of where the people
who were the closest to me

00:08:14.480 --> 00:08:17.770
were extremely
different from me.

00:08:19.170 --> 00:08:21.255
That made life really fun
and really interesting.

00:08:22.939 --> 00:08:25.230
But surprisingly-- and I'm
going to say "surprisingly,"

00:08:25.230 --> 00:08:28.370
because when I started, I
was your typical 21 year old.

00:08:28.370 --> 00:08:31.810
And I was leaving behind
my friends, and my family,

00:08:31.810 --> 00:08:34.510
and my computer, and TV.

00:08:34.510 --> 00:08:36.990
And I was terrified
that, at times, I

00:08:36.990 --> 00:08:39.235
would be really bored
and really lonely.

00:08:41.059 --> 00:08:43.090
But then when it
was over, I longed

00:08:43.090 --> 00:08:49.590
for the silence and the
solitude that I had discovered,

00:08:49.590 --> 00:08:51.080
as much as I longed
for my friends.

00:08:52.670 --> 00:08:55.045
But the thing I missed most
of all sounds really strange.

00:08:56.180 --> 00:09:01.890
Because I missed how
beautiful I felt on the trail.

00:09:01.890 --> 00:09:07.060
And I promise you, when I
was out there, I was filthy,

00:09:07.060 --> 00:09:08.990
I mean covered in dirt.

00:09:08.990 --> 00:09:10.500
We won't even talk
about the smell.

00:09:10.500 --> 00:09:13.720
Because I don't think you
can put it into words.

00:09:13.720 --> 00:09:17.070
And it's East Coast
smell, which by the way

00:09:17.070 --> 00:09:19.550
is way worse than
West Coast smell.

00:09:21.040 --> 00:09:22.660
Plus, there were
scrapes, bug bites,

00:09:22.660 --> 00:09:24.460
bruises all over my body.

00:09:24.460 --> 00:09:25.370
But here's the thing.

00:09:25.370 --> 00:09:29.730
For five months, I
didn't have a mirror.

00:09:29.730 --> 00:09:32.650
And I don't know if
this is funny or sad,

00:09:32.650 --> 00:09:34.690
but the other week, I
went into a middle school.

00:09:34.690 --> 00:09:36.760
And I literally had
to explain that this

00:09:36.760 --> 00:09:40.020
was before the day of the
selfie, like I wasn't taking

00:09:40.020 --> 00:09:42.910
digital pictures of
myself the entire way.

00:09:42.910 --> 00:09:47.160
Plus, I didn't have billboards,
magazines, or commercials

00:09:47.160 --> 00:09:50.150
telling me what I
should look like.

00:09:51.280 --> 00:09:54.730
So I started to see myself
through my interactions

00:09:54.730 --> 00:09:56.386
with other hikers.

00:09:56.386 --> 00:09:58.150
And if I made
someone else smile,

00:09:58.150 --> 00:09:59.470
that made me feel pretty.

00:10:01.030 --> 00:10:03.050
Also, growing up, I
had always thought

00:10:03.050 --> 00:10:04.400
that nature was beautiful.

00:10:05.940 --> 00:10:10.770
But I had never seen
myself as a part of nature,

00:10:10.770 --> 00:10:14.860
and a part of all that beauty,
until I walked the trail.

00:10:16.490 --> 00:10:19.320
And finally, after
hiking through 14

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:22.750
states-- which I love saying
that on the west coast.

00:10:22.750 --> 00:10:25.840
Because it makes it
sound so far, so long.

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:30.820
But after hiking through
14 states, at that point,

00:10:30.820 --> 00:10:35.044
I based my self worth a whole
lot less on how I looked,

00:10:35.044 --> 00:10:36.710
and a whole lot more
on what I could do.

00:10:38.186 --> 00:10:39.560
And that's the
gift of the trail.

00:10:39.560 --> 00:10:43.316
It makes you realize you can
do so much more than you once

00:10:43.316 --> 00:10:44.190
thought was possible.

00:10:45.600 --> 00:10:49.465
It exposes you to new things,
new horizons, new trails.

00:10:50.490 --> 00:10:52.650
And I decided that
I really wanted

00:10:52.650 --> 00:10:55.062
to do more, on
and off the trail,

00:10:55.062 --> 00:10:56.645
more than I once
thought was possible.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.710
So as time passed, I started
saving up money from work.

00:11:01.710 --> 00:11:04.110
I started saving up
time away from work.

00:11:04.110 --> 00:11:07.396
And I started to plan
another big hike.

00:11:07.396 --> 00:11:09.600
And one of the great
things about being a hiker

00:11:09.600 --> 00:11:12.490
is that there are
trails everywhere,

00:11:12.490 --> 00:11:15.100
I mean all over the
US, all over the world.

00:11:15.100 --> 00:11:17.470
And in my opinion, hiking is
one of the most affordable,

00:11:17.470 --> 00:11:20.062
accessible, and
best ways to travel.

00:11:20.062 --> 00:11:21.520
So I actually want
to take a minute

00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:24.180
and share some of my
favorite hiking pictures

00:11:24.180 --> 00:11:26.927
from different trails around
the world with you all.

00:11:28.270 --> 00:11:30.010
And as the pictures
scroll through,

00:11:30.010 --> 00:11:32.440
I'll try to tell you
where they were taken.

00:11:32.440 --> 00:11:36.045
So we'll start our journey in
Africa at Mount Kilimanjaro.

