00:45:52.432 --> 00:45:53.765
JENNIFER DAVIS: Other questions?

00:45:54.840 --> 00:45:55.340
Yeah?

00:45:55.340 --> 00:45:57.465
AUDIENCE: So before you go
out on these long hikes,

00:45:57.465 --> 00:45:59.208
how do you prepare yourself?

00:45:59.208 --> 00:46:01.580
What kind of training do you do?

00:46:01.580 --> 00:46:04.560
JENNIFER DAVIS: Yeah, I
try to train physically.

00:46:04.560 --> 00:46:07.140
The thing I think is
most helpful is climbing,

00:46:07.140 --> 00:46:08.560
exercises with climbing.

00:46:08.560 --> 00:46:10.760
Cycling is really good.

00:46:10.760 --> 00:46:13.500
I like to wear a heavy
pack even when I train.

00:46:13.500 --> 00:46:15.275
Because it helps
develop those muscles.

00:46:17.080 --> 00:46:19.560
But anything physical
you can do is helpful.

00:46:19.560 --> 00:46:21.670
I think it's important
to prepare emotionally.

00:46:21.670 --> 00:46:23.820
Most people get off for
emotional reasons, not

00:46:23.820 --> 00:46:25.480
physical reasons.

00:46:25.480 --> 00:46:28.570
So be prepared to be away
from friends and family

00:46:28.570 --> 00:46:30.490
and not take showers every day.

00:46:30.490 --> 00:46:32.630
You have to kind of wrap
your head around that.

00:46:34.150 --> 00:46:36.200
And then some people,
really they'll

00:46:36.200 --> 00:46:38.120
just kind of get in
shape on the trail,

00:46:38.120 --> 00:46:39.460
which you can also do that.

00:46:39.460 --> 00:46:41.300
Because with work and
life, sometimes it's

00:46:41.300 --> 00:46:43.550
hard to train or prepare.

00:46:43.550 --> 00:46:45.500
And the most important
thing is to not

00:46:45.500 --> 00:46:47.800
try to go too fast too soon,
or carry too much weight.

00:46:47.800 --> 00:46:50.258
Because then you are more likely
to get injured, especially

00:46:50.258 --> 00:46:51.860
if you haven't gotten ready.

00:46:51.860 --> 00:46:53.830
AUDIENCE: What would
be your favorite hike

00:46:53.830 --> 00:46:56.442
or your favorite place to go?

00:46:57.329 --> 00:46:59.620
JENNIFER DAVIS: The Appalachian
Trail's asked the most.

00:46:59.620 --> 00:47:00.453
It's given the most.

00:47:00.453 --> 00:47:01.530
So it's my favorite.

00:47:01.530 --> 00:47:05.010
But on top of that,
we loved Iceland.

00:47:05.010 --> 00:47:05.980
We love Corsica.

00:47:05.980 --> 00:47:09.530
There's 125 mile trail that
runs the length of Corsica.

00:47:10.670 --> 00:47:12.065
I really liked Peru.

00:47:13.252 --> 00:47:14.835
BREW DAVIS: We did
the Colorado Trail.

00:47:15.960 --> 00:47:19.120
That's about a not quite
500 mile trail from Durango

00:47:19.120 --> 00:47:19.780
to Denver.

00:47:19.780 --> 00:47:21.599
And it's really
stunning, especially,

00:47:21.599 --> 00:47:23.265
in the southern part
closest to Durango.

00:47:25.362 --> 00:47:27.070
Tour de Mont Blanc,
did you mention that?

00:47:27.859 --> 00:47:29.650
JENNIFER DAVIS: It was
in the photos, but--

00:47:29.650 --> 00:47:31.710
BREW DAVIS: Tour de Mont
Blanc-- Italy, France,

00:47:31.710 --> 00:47:33.270
and Switzerland,
that's a good one.

00:47:33.270 --> 00:47:34.630
JENNIFER DAVIS: We'd
do them all again.

00:47:34.630 --> 00:47:35.338
BREW DAVIS: Yeah.

00:47:36.716 --> 00:47:38.090
JENNIFER DAVIS:
It's the problem.

00:47:38.090 --> 00:47:38.590
Yeah?

00:47:38.590 --> 00:47:42.573
AUDIENCE: So I heard there was
a current PCT yo-yo attempt.

00:47:42.573 --> 00:47:45.447
Would you be interested in
doing anything like that?

00:47:46.834 --> 00:47:49.000
JENNIFER DAVIS: For me, the
Appalachian Trail record

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:53.080
was kind of the pinnacle of
these feats of endurance.

00:47:53.080 --> 00:47:55.510
Partly because it's one
of the oldest marks.

00:47:56.630 --> 00:48:00.850
The first person the yo-yo the
PCT, I think it was in 2006.

00:48:00.850 --> 00:48:03.500
So it's a relatively new
thing, and a very hard thing

00:48:03.500 --> 00:48:04.660
to accomplish.

00:48:04.660 --> 00:48:07.250
Plus having a family--
doing it one way

00:48:07.250 --> 00:48:10.910
is going to take, even if you
do it really fast, three months.

00:48:10.910 --> 00:48:14.790
Doing it both ways, you're
gone for half of the year.

00:48:16.500 --> 00:48:19.840
So now, my ultimate goal is
just to get people outdoors

00:48:19.840 --> 00:48:22.450
and to experience the trail
in as many different ways as

00:48:22.450 --> 00:48:23.110
possible.

00:48:23.110 --> 00:48:25.600
And I'm fortunate that
everything lined up

00:48:25.600 --> 00:48:27.700
and I got to try for the record.

00:48:27.700 --> 00:48:31.140
But now we're section hikers,
meaning we do it in pieces.

00:48:31.140 --> 00:48:33.170
And we have the guiding
company at home,

00:48:33.170 --> 00:48:34.950
so we get people
outdoors that way.

00:48:34.950 --> 00:48:37.720
And it's good.

00:48:37.720 --> 00:48:39.260
We take our daughter outside.

00:48:39.260 --> 00:48:41.210
It's definitely
a different pace.

00:48:41.210 --> 00:48:41.930
It's not better.

00:48:41.930 --> 00:48:42.630
It's not worse.

00:48:42.630 --> 00:48:45.185
It's just all about seasons.

00:48:45.185 --> 00:48:48.090
AUDIENCE: How much time did
you spend planning this hike?

00:48:48.090 --> 00:48:49.090
BREW DAVIS: Very little.

00:48:50.420 --> 00:48:51.460
We have a friend.

00:48:53.450 --> 00:48:56.940
He knows the roads around the
Appalachian Trail really well.

00:48:56.940 --> 00:49:00.480
Because he himself
has hiked it 17 times.

00:49:00.480 --> 00:49:02.610
And he's also run
support for people.

00:49:02.610 --> 00:49:08.940
And so before we started hiking,
we got the data book out.

00:49:08.940 --> 00:49:11.030
And he would highlight
roads and say,

00:49:11.030 --> 00:49:13.580
these are the roads that
you should focus on.

00:49:14.800 --> 00:49:20.380
And I was teaching middle
school until the day

00:49:20.380 --> 00:49:22.130
before we left for the trail.

00:49:23.390 --> 00:49:27.580
And I think I also had sort of
banked knowledge of the trail

00:49:27.580 --> 00:49:29.920
from when she did it in
2008, and I had already

00:49:29.920 --> 00:49:30.590
done a support.

00:49:30.590 --> 00:49:33.526
So for her, it was she knew
what she was going to do.

00:49:33.526 --> 00:49:34.650
She was just going to hike.

00:49:34.650 --> 00:49:38.600
For me, it was using
prior knowledge

00:49:38.600 --> 00:49:42.740
and our friend's
knowledge to not get

00:49:42.740 --> 00:49:43.940
turned around on the roads.

00:49:43.940 --> 00:49:45.660
And I have a pretty good
sense of direction, too.

00:49:45.660 --> 00:49:46.710
So I could rely on that.

00:49:46.710 --> 00:49:49.390
So we didn't really plan
that part very much at all.

00:49:49.390 --> 00:49:51.190
And we kind of
did it on the fly,

00:49:51.190 --> 00:49:54.640
realized that we needed-- it
might be beneficial for Jen

00:49:54.640 --> 00:49:56.377
to have some people
to hike with her

00:49:56.377 --> 00:49:57.710
and give her some help that way.

00:49:57.710 --> 00:49:58.590
JENNIFER DAVIS: Yeah.

00:49:58.590 --> 00:50:03.080
AUDIENCE: After all this
journey of life that you have,

00:50:03.080 --> 00:50:06.020
how can Jennifer define herself?

00:50:07.490 --> 00:50:10.030
JENNIFER DAVIS: Not by
hiking, surprisingly.

00:50:11.670 --> 00:50:14.190
That's been key for me,
even going for the record,

00:50:14.190 --> 00:50:17.580
is I thought, I
have to be fulfilled

00:50:17.580 --> 00:50:19.380
whether we set this or not.

00:50:19.380 --> 00:50:24.210
And the trail for me, that
first journey was so important.

00:50:24.210 --> 00:50:26.610
Because it taught me
it's OK to just be me.

00:50:26.610 --> 00:50:27.110
It is.

00:50:27.110 --> 00:50:30.570
And the natural setting
helps you feel natural.

00:50:30.570 --> 00:50:32.100
It helps you be yourself.

00:50:32.100 --> 00:50:35.140
But being a hiker
doesn't define me.

00:50:35.140 --> 00:50:38.890
I have a really wonderful
family and a strong faith.

00:50:38.890 --> 00:50:42.970
And as long as I can, I'm going
to hike, and walk, and run.

00:50:42.970 --> 00:50:44.840
But it's not the only thing.

00:50:45.960 --> 00:50:50.210
So I think what frustrated
me about the questions

00:50:50.210 --> 00:50:51.940
is everyone focused
on the end result.

00:50:51.940 --> 00:50:53.990
No one asked about
what got us there.

00:50:53.990 --> 00:50:56.109
And no one realized
that the things that

00:50:56.109 --> 00:50:57.650
helped us do well
on the record could

00:50:57.650 --> 00:51:01.030
be applied to anything in life.

00:51:01.030 --> 00:51:03.630
We run a small company,
and the trail--

00:51:03.630 --> 00:51:03.966
BREW DAVIS: It's going to be
like Google in a few years,

00:51:03.966 --> 00:51:04.000
probably.

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:05.310
JENNIFER DAVIS: --was
my business school.

00:51:05.310 --> 00:51:06.340
Yeah, it's going to
be just like Google.

00:51:06.340 --> 00:51:07.950
BREW DAVIS: Right now,
it's kind of small.

00:51:07.950 --> 00:51:08.900
JENNIFER DAVIS: But the
trail was my business school.

00:51:08.900 --> 00:51:11.441
It taught me how to budget, and
work with all different types

00:51:11.441 --> 00:51:13.470
of people, and not give up.

